{"questionId":"9086713","questionHtml":"<p>Monochromatic light of frequency <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> is incident on the surface of a metal. The stopping voltage for this light is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>. When the frequency of the radiation is changed to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, the stopping voltage is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p>\n<p>What is the quantity&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math> equal to?</p>\n<p><br>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>h</mi><mi>e</mi></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mi>e</mi></mfrac></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>B</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9086713","referenceCode":"SPM.1A.HL.TZ0.39","subjectId":"59-dp-physics-first-assessment-2025","title":"Monochromatic light of frequency f1 is incident on the surface of a metal. The stopping voltage for this light is V1. When the frequency of the radiation is changed to f2, the stop","paper":"1A","level":"HL","questionNumber":"39","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E. Nuclear and quantum physics","E.2 Quantum physics"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}